<br>
I have a 55 gallon saltwater reef tank in my living room and have a 100 gallon acrylic tank and almost all the accessories in my basement waiting for my slack ass to finish the bar I want to build it into.  I ended up getting a very good deal buying the 100g and stuff to go with it for $800 used from the employee bulletin board at work but if I were to start from scratch and buy everything new I would guess to have more than $3000 in it.  In addition to the tank and accessories I will need at least $500 worth of live rock, $100 worth of sand/araganite<br>
<br>
You can cut some costs by building your own sump and there are several DIY projects online to build your own denitrator, calcium reactor, light fixtures, etc.  If you are a tinkerer you can save alot of cash but the cost still gets out of hand.<br>
<br>
IMO freshwater is much easier to maintain,  hell I had a 55 gallon freshwater tank for nearly 8 years before I switched to saltwater and in that 8 years the only time I ever added a chemical, changed water, or did ANYTHING to it was when I moved and had to set it back up.  The water was crystal clear all the time and I never lost fish.  For Saltwater even if you are making an FO (fish only) tank you need to check levels and add alot of chemicals(expensive chemicals).  If you don't wanna change water all the time and want a salt tank that is more maintenance free,  then you start spending tons of cash on filters and such.  Right from the start you DO NOT want to make a saltwater tank by just adding seasalt to tap water, you will want to either purchase water from your lfs &quot;local fish store&quot; for about 50-75 cents a gallon or get an HO filter.  My HO filter was $300 and after the first week makes about 5 gallons of clean water per week. <br>
<br>
If you are ok with spending some time and money a Saltwater tank is very rewarding and beautiful but if you would like something cheap and easy that is just neat to look at....freshwater all the way!  Just a warning....if you go saltwater....its like an addiction....first you say you will just make a cheap one and you don't need all the fancy gadgets....but then you keep spending more and more time and money to make your tank perfect.<br>
<br>
